'''Agallis''' ([[ancient Greek|Gr.]] '''{{lang|grc|Ἀγαλλίς}}''', [[floruit|fl.]] 2nd century BC) of [[Corcyra]] was a female [[Philologist|grammarian]] who wrote about [[Homer]], according to [[Athenaeus]].<ref>[[Athenaeus]], ''[[Deipnosophistae]]'' i. p. 14, d.</ref>  Some scholars believe her to have belonged to the [[hetaera]]e class.<ref>{{cite book  | last =Hecker  | first =Eugene Arthur  | title =A Short History of Women's Rights from the Days of Augustus to the Present Time  | publisher =[[G. P. Putnam's Sons]]  | year =1914  | location =New York City  | pages =42  | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=igIMJp5q6wMC&pg=PA42&dq=agallis}}</ref>  She attributed the invention of ball games to [[Nausicaa]], one of her countrywomen, and most later writers took her bias in this matter as self-evident.  Her writings are no longer extant.<ref>{{cite book  | last =Pomeroy  | first =Sarah B.  | title =Women in Hellenistic Egypt: From Alexander to Cleopatra  | publisher =[[Wayne State University Press]]  | year =1990  | location =Detroit  | pages =61  | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=lcH6oWafBq8C&pg=PA61&dq=agallis  | isbn = 0-8143-2230-1}}</ref>

Some have supposed from two passages in the ''[[Suda]]'' that we ought to read "Anagallis" in this passage of Athenaeus.<ref>[[Suda]], ''s.v.'' {{lang|grc|Ἀνάγαλλις}} and {{lang|grc|Ὄρχησις}}</ref>  The [[scholiast]] on Homer and [[Eustathius of Thessalonica|Eustathius]]<ref>''ad Il.'' xviii. 491</ref> mention a grammarian of the name of Agallias, a pupil of [[Aristophanes of Byzantium|Aristophanes the grammarian]], also a [[Corcyra]]ean and a commentator upon Homer, who may be the same as Agallis, or perhaps her father.<ref>{{Cite book  | last = Smith  | first = William  | author-link = William Smith (lexicographer)  | contribution = Agallis  | editor-last = Smith  | editor-first = William  | title = [[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]  | volume = 1  | pages = 5  | place = Boston  | year = 1870  | contribution-url = http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0066.html}}</ref>

For a time in the 19th century, the name "Agallis" was thought to be the subject of one of the poems of [[Sappho]].  Later scholarship showed this to have been an erroneous interpretation of a corrupted text.<ref>{{cite book  | last =Parsons  | first =Peter  |author2=T.P. Wiseman (ed.)  | title =Classics in Progress: Essays on Ancient Greece and Rome  | publisher =[[Oxford University Press]]  | year =2006  | location =Oxford  | pages =53  | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=7_ddt_LSl_wC&pg=PA53&dq=agallis  | isbn = 0-19-726323-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book  | last =Bülow-Jacobsen  | first =Adam  | title =Proceedings of the 20th International Congress of Papyrologists  | publisher =[[Museum Tusculanum Press]]  | year =1992  | location =Copenhagen  | pages =121  | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=QOYO2qHYOU4C&pg=PA121&dq=agallis  | isbn = 87-7289-264-1}}</ref>

