'''Hasan al-Rammah''' (died 1295) was an [[Arab]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Elgood|first1=Robert|title=Firearms of the Islamic World: In the Tared Rajab Museum, Kuwait|date=1995|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=9781850439639|url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=epaMx7jSZjIC&pg=PA20&dq=Hasan+al-Rammah+arab&hl=ar&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjX9dzggv3YAhUBmhQKHRufBAY4ChDoAQgkMAA#v=onepage&q=Hasan%20al-Rammah%20arab&f=false|language=en}}</ref> [[chemist]] and [[engineer]] during the [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk Sultanate]] who studied [[gunpowder]]s and [[explosive]]s, and sketched prototype instruments of warfare, including what some have maintained is a [[torpedo]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Hinds, Joseph |url=http://greathistory.com/very-very-early-torpedoes.htm |title=Very, Very Early Torpedoes |publisher=Great History |date=23 February 2009 |accessdate=26 November 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102114555/http://greathistory.com/very-very-early-torpedoes.htm |archivedate=2 November 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Williamson, Mitch |url=http://weaponsandwarfare.com/?p=16618 |title=Hassan Al Rammah |publisher=Weapons and Warfare <nowiki>|</nowiki> Military History and Hardware |date=21 April 2013 |accessdate=26 November 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117002101/http://weaponsandwarfare.com/?p=16618 |archivedate=17 November 2013 |df= }}</ref>
