{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image | Ship image= I-176.jpg | Ship caption=[[Sister ship]] ''I-176'' at sea, 1942 }} {{Infobox ship career | Hide header= | Ship country=[[Empire of Japan]] | Ship flag= {{shipboxflag|Empire of Japan|naval}} | Ship name= ''I-185'' | Ship ordered= | Ship awarded= | Ship builder=[[Yokosuka Naval Arsenal]] | Ship original cost= | Ship yard number= | Ship way number= | Ship laid down=9 February 1942, as ''I-85'' | Ship launched=16 September 1943 | Ship sponsor= | Ship christened= | Ship completed=23 September 1943 | Ship struck=10 September 1944 | Ship renamed=1942, as ''I-182'' | Ship fate=Sunk by {{USS|Newcomb|DD-586|6}}, 22 June 1944 | Ship notes= | Ship badge= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics | Hide header= | Header caption= |Ship class=[[Kaidai type submarine|''Kaidai'' type]], [[Kaidai type submarine#Kaidai VII (I-176 class)|''KD7''-class]] |Ship displacement=*{{Convert|1833|LT|t|0|disp=flip|abbr=on}} surfaced * {{Convert|2602|LT|t|0|disp=flip|abbr=on}} submerged |Ship length={{convert|105.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}} |Ship beam={{convert|8.25|m|ftin|abbr=on}} |Ship draft={{convert|4.6|m|ftin|abbr=on}} |Ship power=*{{convert|8000|bhp|lk=in|abbr=on}} (diesels) * {{convert|1800|hp|abbr=on}} (electric motors) |Ship propulsion=*[[Diesel-electric]] * 2 × [[diesel engine]]s * 2 × [[electric motor]]s |Ship speed=*{{convert|23|kn|lk=in}} surfaced * {{convert|8|kn}} submerged |Ship range=*{{convert|8000|nmi|abbr=on|lk=in}} at {{convert|16|kn}} surfaced * {{convert|50|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|5|kn}} submerged |Ship endurance= |Ship test depth={{convert|80|m|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship complement=86 |Ship armament=*6 × {{convert|533|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s (all bow) * 1 × [[Type 3 120 mm 45 caliber naval gun|{{convert|120|mm|in|abbr=on}}]] [[deck gun]] * 1 × twin [[Type 96 25 mm AT/AA Gun|{{convert|25|mm|abbr=on|1}} Type 96]] [[AA gun]] }} |} The '''Japanese submarine ''I-185''''' (originally '''''I-85''''') was a [[Kaidai type submarine|''Kaidai'' type]] [[cruiser submarine]] of the KD7 [[ship class|sub-class]] built for the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] (IJN) during the 1940s. She was sunk with all hands by an American [[destroyer]] during the [[Battle of the Philippine Sea]] in mid-1944.
==Design and description== The submarines of the KD7 sub-class were medium-range attack submarines developed from the preceding KD6 sub-class. They [[Displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{Convert|1833|LT|t|0|disp=flip|sp=us}} surfaced and {{Convert|2602|LT|t|0|disp=flip|sp=us}} submerged. The submarines were {{convert|105.5|m|ftin|sp=us}} long, had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|8.25|m|ftin|sp=us}} and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|4.6|m|ftin|sp=us}}. The boats had a diving depth of {{convert|80|m|ft|abbr=on}} and a complement of 86 officers and crewmen.<ref name=cd3>Carpenter & Polmar, p. 105</ref>
For surface running, the boats were powered by two {{convert|4000|bhp|lk=in|0|adj=on}} [[diesel engine]]s, each driving one [[propeller shaft]]. When submerged each propeller was driven by a {{convert|900|hp|0|adj=on}} [[electric motor]]. They could reach {{convert|23|kn|lk=in}} on the surface and {{convert|8|kn}} underwater. On the surface, the KD7s had a range of {{convert|8000|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|16|kn}}; submerged, they had a range of {{convert|50|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|5|kn}}.<ref name=c5>Chesneau, p. 199</ref>
The boats were armed with six internal {{convert|53.3|cm|in|1|abbr=on|sp=us}} [[torpedo tube]]s, all in the bow. They carried one reload for each tube; a total of a dozen [[torpedo]]es. They were originally intended to be armed with two twin-gun mounts for the [[Type 96 25 mm AT/AA Gun|{{convert|25|mm|abbr=on|1}} Type 96]] [[anti-aircraft gun]], but a [[Type 3 120 mm 45 caliber naval gun|{{convert|120|mm|in|abbr=on}}]] [[deck gun]] for combat on the surface was substituted for one 25&nbsp;mm mount during construction.<ref name=b4>Bagnasco, pp. 183, 186</ref>
==Construction and career== Built by the [[Yokosuka Naval Arsenal]], the boat was [[laid down]] on 9 February 1942<ref name=hk/> as ''I-85'' and renamed ''I-185'' in 1942. She was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 16 September 1943 and completed on 23 September.<ref name=cd3/> The boat was sunk with the loss of all 95 officers and crewmen aboard by the destroyer {{USS|Newcomb|DD-586|6}} on 22 June 1944 near [[Saipan]]. ''I-185'' was stricken from the [[Navy List]] on 10 September 1944.<ref name=hk>Hackett & Kingsepp</ref>
